React isn't magic.

It's just JavaScript that returns HTML.

Example

function Header() {
    return (
        <h1>Links Vault</h1>
    );
}

Nothing special.

Just a function.

Rule #2
Everything starts with data.

Never think

"I need a form."

Think

"What data am I storing?"

For this project:

Link

↓

Title

URL

Description

Tags

Immediately imagine

interface Link{
    id:number;
    title:string;
    url:string;
    description:string;
    tags:string[];
}

If you can't define the data...

You can't build the application.

Always define data FIRST.

Rule #3

Think in nouns.

If I say

Spotify

You immediately think

Song

Album

Playlist

Artist

User

Those become interfaces.

If I say

Bank

Customer

Account

Transaction

If I say

School

Student

Teacher

Subject

Mark

If I say

Links Vault

Link

One noun.

One interface.

Rule #4

Everything in React is either

DATA

or

UI

Nothing else.

Data

↓

Links

UI

↓

Cards

Buttons

Forms

Search

Never mix them in your head.

Rule #5

Always ask

"Who owns the data?"

This is the biggest beginner mistake.

Example

LinkCard

Should LinkCard store all links?

No.

Why?

It only displays ONE.

Who owns the array?

App.tsx

Always.

Think

App

↓

owns everything

↓

Children borrow it
Rule #6

State is memory.

Imagine React has amnesia.

Every render it forgets everything.

State says

"Remember this."

Without state

Click Add

↓

Reload

↓

Gone

State

Click Add

↓

Remember

↓

Display
Rule #7

Props are gifts.

Parent

↓

gives

↓

Child

Child never steals.

Child never edits.

Child simply uses.

Rule #8

Every button answers ONE question.

Delete button?

Question

Which link?

Needs

id

Edit?

Question

Which link?

Needs

id

Search?

Question

What text?

Needs

search

Always ask

"What information does this button need?"

Rule #9

Every application follows

INPUT

↓

STATE

↓

OUTPUT

For Links Vault

Input

↓

Form

↓

State

↓

Links Array

↓

Output

↓

